## `test_fuse_fcntl_posix_range_lock(mount)`
<!-- checksum: placeholder-flock-4 -->
<!-- trace: skipped -->
<!-- trace_skip_reason: syscall boundary + subprocess -->

### Purpose
Two subprocesses take POSIX (fcntl F_SETLK) exclusive locks on non-overlapping ranges — both succeed. Overlapping ranges → the second call raises EAGAIN.

### Postconditions

```python
path = mount / "ranged"
path.write_bytes(b"x" * 1000)

# F_SETLK struct (little-endian, platform-dependent; use struct "hhllh" per Linux)
# type (int16), whence (int16), start (int64), len (int64), pid (int16)
LOCK_STRUCT = "hhllh"

p1 = _worker(f"""
    import fcntl, struct, time
    f = open({str(path)!r}, 'rb+')
    lock = struct.pack({LOCK_STRUCT!r}, fcntl.F_WRLCK, 0, 0, 100, 0)
    fcntl.fcntl(f, fcntl.F_SETLK, lock)
    print('P1', flush=True)
    time.sleep(10)
""")
assert p1.stdout.readline().strip() == b"P1"

# Non-overlapping range from another process: OK.
with open(path, "rb+") as f:
    lock = struct.pack(LOCK_STRUCT, fcntl.F_WRLCK, 0, 100, 100, 0)
    fcntl.fcntl(f, fcntl.F_SETLK, lock)   # no error
    fcntl.fcntl(f, fcntl.F_SETLK, struct.pack(LOCK_STRUCT, fcntl.F_UNLCK, 0, 100, 100, 0))

# Overlapping range: EAGAIN.
with open(path, "rb+") as f:
    lock = struct.pack(LOCK_STRUCT, fcntl.F_WRLCK, 0, 50, 100, 0)
    with pytest.raises(OSError) as e:
        fcntl.fcntl(f, fcntl.F_SETLK, lock)
    assert e.value.errno in (errno.EAGAIN, errno.EACCES)

p1.kill()
p1.wait()
```

